                <h5 class="card-title text-align: right;">Ingredients<br>Pozole</h5>
                <li>3 pounds boneless pork shoulder, cut into inch-thick pieces</li>
                <li>2 containers (32 ounces each) chicken broth</li>
                <li>2 bay leaves</li>
                <li>2 tsp whole mexican oregano</li>
                <li>1 tsp coriander leaves or cilantro</li>
                <li>1 tsp salt</li>
                <li>1/2 tsp ground black pepper</li>
                <li>3 cans (15 ounces each) hominy corn, drained and rinsed</li>
                <br>
                <h5>Chili sauce</h5>
                <li>2 El Guapo Pasilla Ancho Chili Pods, stemmed and seeded (approximately 1 ounce)</li>
                <li>2 El Guapo Guajillo Whole Chili Pods, stemmed and seeded (about 1 ounce)</li>
                <li>1 cup of boiling water</li>
                <li>1/2 cup of water</li>
                <li>1 large white onion, peeled and quartered</li>
                <li>3 cloves of fresh garlic</li>
                <li>2 whole cloves</li>
                <li>1/2 tsp ground cumin</li>
                <li>1/2 tsp salt</li>
                <br>
                <h5 class="card-title text-align: right;">Preparation</h5>
                <p class="card-text">For the Pozole, place the pork and broth in a 5-quart saucepan. Bring to a boil over high heat, 
                  skimming to remove foam from the surface. Add the bay leaves, oregano, cilantro, salt and pepper. 
                  Reduce heat to medium-low; and cover the pot. Cook over low heat for 1 1/2 hours or until meat is tender.<br><br>
                  Meanwhile, for the sauce, place the chiles in a large heatproof bowl. Add boiling water; and then cover it. 
                  Soak chiles 30 minutes or until softened. Remove chiles with tongs or slotted spoon and transfer to blender bowl, 
                  discarding liquid from chiles. Add remaining 1/2 cup water, onion, garlic, cloves, cumin and salt; and cover the blender. 
                  Blend on high speed until well blended. Reserve.<br><br>
                  Transfer the pork to a large bowl, reserving the cooking liquid in the pot. 
                  Cut pork into large chunks with 2 forks. Return the pork to the pot. Add the hominy corn and the prepared chili sauce; 
                  and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to medium-low; cook over low heat for 30 minutes.<br><br>
                  Serve the pozole in deep plates. Add sliced radishes, fresh cilantro, minced onion, and lemon, if desired.</p>
                
